mber 1, 1934) -- tAppendix II: Excerpt from NKVD Operational Order 00447 -- tAppendix III: Operational Order No. 00486 -- tChronology -- tSelected Glossary of Names, Places, and Institutions -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRoughly ten million children were victims of political repression in the Soviet Union during the Stalinist era, the sons and daughters of peasants, workers, scientists, physicians, and political leaders considered by the regime to be dangerous to the political order. Ten grown victims, who as children suffered banishment, starvation, disease, anti-Semitism, and trauma resulting from their parents’ condemnation and arrest, now freely share their stories.  The result is a powerful and moving oral history that will profoundly deepen the reader’s understanding of life in the U.S.S.R. under the despotic reign of Joseph Stalin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommunismxSocial aspectszSoviet Union. 0aPolitical prisonerszSoviet UnionvBiography. 0aPolitical prisonerszSoviet UnionvInterviews. 0aPolitical purgeszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zSoviet Union. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aDubrovina, Irina Andreevna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKostina, Vera Mikhailovna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKozyrev, Aleksandr Nikolaevich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevitina, Maya Rudolfovna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorozova, Tamara Nikolaevna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuravsky, Valentin Tikhonovich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShik